# Development Standards

How code should be designed and written. Git workflow lives in `git-workflow.mdc`.

## 1. Code Design

- Enforce separation of concerns
- Prefer composition over inheritance
- Apply SOLID principles when they improve maintainability
- Keep functions and components small and single-purpose
- Use early returns to reduce nesting
- Prefer pure functions where possible
- Prefer consistent patterns over clever one-off solutions
- Do not introduce quick hacks without clearly flagging them

## 2. TypeScript Discipline

- Use TypeScript types heavily wherever possible
- Prefer explicit types at boundaries: inputs, params, return values, API data, store state, and config objects
- Avoid `any`; if unavoidable, explain why
- If a type or interface becomes too large or confusing, split it into smaller reusable types
- Handle `null` / `undefined` intentionally, not implicitly

## 3. Readability & Maintainability

- Clean, readable code is the default goal
- Write code for the next reader, not just runtime correctness
- Extract repeated logic into utilities, services, or shared helpers
- Avoid magic strings/numbers; use named constants
- Minimize comments; only add them when intent is not obvious
- Prefer immutable updates over mutating shared state

## 4. Async, Reactivity & Error Handling

- Services should return `Observable`; convert to signals at the consumption site with `toSignal()` or subscribe in stores
- Use `takeUntilDestroyed()` from `@angular/core/rxjs-interop` for subscription cleanup — preferred over manual `DestroyRef.onDestroy`
- Prefer `async/await` over `.then()` / `.catch()` chains when working with promises
- Keep async flows readable and explicit
- Fail loudly for invalid states; do not silently swallow errors — surface or log them clearly

## 5. Angular Conventions

### Architecture

- Standalone-only — never introduce `@NgModule`
- Zoneless — the app uses `provideZonelessChangeDetection()`; do not add `zone.js` or rely on Zone-based change detection
- Keep components presentational; push logic into stores, services, or helpers
- Preserve existing UX and animation behavior unless the task explicitly changes it

### Dependency Injection

- Always use the `inject()` function — never constructor-parameter DI
- Write guards, interceptors, and resolvers as functions (not classes)

### Signals

- Use `signal()`, `computed()`, `effect()` as the primary reactivity model
- Use `input()` / `output()` signal APIs — never `@Input()` / `@Output()` decorators
- Use `model()` for two-way binding scenarios instead of `@Input()` + `@Output()` pairs
- Prefer `viewChild()` / `viewChildren()` signal queries for new code; migrate legacy `@ViewChild()` / `@ViewChildren()` usages when touching those files and the change is low-risk
- Prefer `linkedSignal()` when you need a writable signal derived from another signal
- Prefer `toSignal()` to bridge RxJS observables into the signal graph when it improves clarity; use `toObservable()` for the reverse when needed

### Templates

- Use built-in control flow: `@if`, `@for` (with `track`), `@switch`, `@empty` — never `*ngIf`, `*ngFor`, `*ngSwitch`
- Use `@defer` blocks when they meaningfully improve loading behavior for heavy UI (charts, markdown renderers, etc.)

### Data Loading

- Prefer `resource()` / `httpResource()` for new signal-driven async flows when they make the data lifecycle clearer; do not refactor stable code only to adopt them
- Prefer `afterNextRender()` for one-time DOM setup and `afterRender()` for render-driven side effects when they improve clarity; avoid replacing stable lifecycle hooks without a clear benefit

### Routing

- Lazy-load via `loadComponent()` — no `loadChildren` with module arrays
- Prefer `withComponentInputBinding()` when route params map cleanly to component `input()` signals and the route is being actively changed

### Material

- Import Angular Material modules per component — no shared barrel module

## 6. State Management

- Use `@ngrx/signals` `signalStore` for feature state (stores live under `app/store/` or colocated with the feature)
- Lightweight app-wide state (theme, recently-viewed) can use a plain `@Injectable` with `signal()` / `computed()`
- Do not introduce `@ngrx/store`, `@ngrx/effects`, or any classic Redux-style state layer
- Use `patchState()` for immutable state updates inside `withMethods`

## 7. Nx Monorepo

- Respect `@nx/enforce-module-boundaries` — shared types/utils in `libs/shared/*`, server-only code in `libs/server/*`
- Run all tasks through `pnpm nx` — never call underlying tooling directly
- Use `nx g` for scaffolding new projects or libraries

## 8. Styling

- Use SCSS; follow Angular Material theming conventions (`@use '@angular/material' as mat`)
- Colocate component styles (inline or `.component.scss`)
- Use Material design tokens / theme API over hardcoded color values

## 9. Testing Stance

- No unit tests required per project decision
- Verify correctness with `pnpm nx run-many -t lint` and `npx tsc --noEmit` before committing
- Do not generate test files unless the user explicitly asks
